<TEXT>
a federal judge dismissed new charges against 
a figure in the defense industry probe friday saying a second 
indictment was an act of revenge because the man was appealing his 
conviction on earlier charges 
thomas e muldoon a former consultant to norden systems 
already had been convicted on eight felonies including conspiracy 
and bribery of a public official soon after his attorney filed an 
appeal on that conviction muldoon was indicted on charges of 
trafficking in secret defense information 
us district judge albert v bryan jr in alexandria va 
wrote that there was a realistic likelihood of vindictiveness on 
the part of the united states in causing the return of the present 
indictment in retaliation for the defendant thomas e muldoons 
going to trial or noting an appeal for his prior conviction or 
both 
muldoon 60 was sentenced to 27 months in prison and fined 
10000 for his conviction arising from the investigation of fraud 
in defense procurement code named ill wind 
muldoons lawyer albert j ahern jr told the washington post 
that the second indictment against his client was to send a message 
to other defendants in the case to take the plea agreement as 
tendered or face a splitting of the charges and multicount 
indictments as the certain consequence 
