<TEXT>
abcs twin peaks is continuing its downward 
slide in the ratings despite being one of tvs most writtenabout 
new shows this year nielsen audience estimates showed friday 
ratings for thursdays episode showed that it was seen in nine 
million fewer homes than the twohour april 8 premiere of the david 
lynch series the premiere was seen in more than 194 million homes 
and ranked fifth nationally in ratings for that week 
although its 113 rating made the show second in ratings in its 
onehour time period thursday it only drew 18 percent of the 
audience then compared to 33 percent for the shows premiere 
nbcs cheers and wings easily beat twin peaks on 
thursday averaging a 194 rating cbs falcon crest was a 
distant third with an 81 average each ratings point represents 
921000 homes 
twin peaks a surreal soap opera set in the pacific 
northwest has been acclaimed by most critics but it also has 
steadily lost audiences each week since its muchpublicized 
premiere 
i think whats happening is that the show is solidifying 
around its core audience of young adults said alan wurtzel 
senior vice president for research at abc he said he thought its 
ratings will stabilize now 
the show has lost most of its viewers in two categories women 
over 50 and men over 35 he said 
but it also has lost occasional viewers of television who may 
have watched the show becase of all the hype and word of mouth 
about the series he said i think what youre seeing is the 
inevitable shakeout 
although the twin peaks premiere did much better than abc 
had expected to a certain extent im disappointed that it didnt 
hold the higher numbers in episodes shown afterwards he said 
