<TEXT>
education officials approved a plan for 
rewriting new yorks elementary and highschool history lessons to 
include more about the contributions of minority americans 
the plan calls for appointment of a 20member committee of 
academics and others to decide on such matters as teacher 
retraining and selection of textbooks for the nations 
thirdlargest public school system 
it was approved friday by the state board of regents at the 
request of education commissioner thomas sobol who said his staff 
has already held talks with educators in other states about 
approaching textbook publishers 
the board approved the idea of rewriting the history curriculum 
in february and on friday endorsed sobols blueprint for getting 
the job done by 1992 
the vote followed more of the acrimonious debate that erupted 
following release last summer of a report by another 
sobolappointed committee which charged the states textbooks were 
filled with hidden assumptions of white supremacy 
that report said new yorks history courses minimize the 
contributions of minorities and largely ignore the wrongs committed 
against nonwhites by whites one of the reasons minority children 
do poorly in school is because they dont read about their 
ancestors in history texts the report said 
without naming the review committee sobol set strict guidelines 
on who it would include elementary middle and high school 
teachers school administrators department heads college 
professors and scholars in social studies 
committee members will be appointed on the basis of racial and 
ethnic diversity sobol said the 17member committee that 
delivered the original critique of states curriculum included one 
white member 
one regent former teacher adelaide sanford of new york city 
worried that the new committee would water down recommendations 
made by last summers task force she accused the regents of 
retreating from a commitment to wipe bias from schools because of 
concern about inflammatory language in the report 
a representative of new york states largest teachers union 
urged a careful approach to the rewrite 
i have grave concerns that we maintain the theory that we as 
americans share a common culture said antonia cortese first 
vice president of new york state united teachers our very basis 
for a democracy is tolerance for other people its not 
separatism 
the regents approved the plan on a unanimous voice vote sanford 
sat silent 
sobol said in february that he had begun discussions with 
educators in other states including california about presenting a 
common front in requesting changes from textbook publishers ahead 
of new york texas has the nations largest school system and 
californias is second 
</TEXT>
