<TEXT>
some members of congress upset over president 
bushs removal of japan from a hit list of unfair traders are 
introducing legislation to take away the presidents discretion in 
the matter 
the bill is just one example of the firestorm created by the 
administrations decision friday to remove japan from a list of 
countries deemed to have erected the most offensive barriers to the 
sale of us products 
sen robert byrd dwva took to the senate floor to declare 
that he was thunderstruck by the action 
excuse me mr president but this boggles the mind he 
said letting japan off the hook is a serious mistake and i think 
congress ought to take a look at it 
the dispute involves the toughest section of the 1988 trade law 
known as super 301 it required the administration to target 
countries in 1989 and 1990 for intensive negotiations aimed at 
removing trade barriers 
if the negotiations were unsuccessful then the administration 
had the power to retaliate with higher us tariffs on imports from 
the offending country 
last year the administration named japan brazil and india but 
this year bush said he was retaining only india because of that 
countrys refusal to remove its barriers to foreign investment and 
foreign insurance companies 
the administration dropped japan and brazil from the list 
because of marketopening moves they have made 
while the super 301 provision was due to expire after this year 
several members of congress said they planned to push for it to be 
extended indefinitely thus forcing the administration to face the 
question of targeting japan in future years 
two senators democrat carl levin of michigan and republican 
arlen specter of pennsylvania said they planned to introduce a 
bill taking away the administrations discretion over whether to 
target japan 
their measure would require the president to target any country 
for negotiations if its trade surplus accounted for 15 percent or 
more of americas overall trade deficit 
last year that provision would have only applied to japan 
americas 49 billion deficit with japan accounted for 45 percent 
of the total us trade deficit of 109 billion 
owen bieber president of the united auto workers supported a 
move to limit the presidents discretion saying that the 
administrations decision friday added insult to injury by 
reaching the preposterous conclusion that japan suddenly deserves a 
clean bill of trade health 
but the administration defended its action saying that 
targeting tokyo again would have undermined the efforts of japanese 
prime minister toshiki kaifu to reform his countrys trade 
practices 
we believe that the most effective way to achieve results is 
through cooperation not confrontation said us trade 
representative carla hills 
commerce secretary robert mosbacher said the message to japan 
was congratulations on a job well done to date 
the administration pledged to keep pressure on japan to live up 
to its commitments including insisting that monitoring provisions 
be placed in an agreement reached april 5 to attack a broad array 
of structural barriers blocking american and other foreign 
companies from doing business in japan 
but many members of congress accused the administration of 
making a serious tactical error they said removing japan from the 
target list took pressure off kaifus government 
when we have a persistent 49 billion trade deficit with japan 
and that nation will not abide by a variety of agreements freeing 
them from the threat of trade sanctions makes no objective sense 
said house majority leader richard gephardt 
a year ago japan was cited for barriers to sales of usmade 
supercomputers satellites and wood products in the past month 
us and japanese negotiators have reached marketopening 
agreements in all three areas 
brazil was targeted for restrictive import licensing practices 
hills said recently enacted legislation in that country should meet 
us concerns in this area 
but india which was cited last year for a ban on operations of 
foreign private insurance companies and for controls on foreign 
investment that distort trade has refused to make concessions the 
1990 target list names those barriers again 
the indian government issued a statement saying it would 
continue to refuse to negotiate bilaterally under threat of 
sanctions 
members of congress said it made no sense to target india with 
its modest 850 million trade surplus with the united states and 
neglect japan whose trade surplus is more than 50 times higher 
in a separate action friday the administration said it was not 
targeting any country for possible sanctions relating to violations 
of us copyright and patent protections 
however it placed four countries brazil india china and 
thailand on a priority watch list as countries deserving 
special attention 
another 19 countries with lesser problems were placed on a watch 
list they were argentina canada chile colombia egypt greece 
indonesia italy japan south korea malaysia pakistan 
philippines saudi arabia spain taiwan turkey venezuela and 
yugoslavia 
