<TEXT>
the chairman of a soviet parliamentary 
delegation says he will try to find out which soviet official 
rejected offers of international aid after the 1986 explosion at 
the chernobyl nuclear reactor 
with the full dimensions of the chernobyl disaster now becoming 
clear the supreme soviet has reversed course and is urgently 
seeking scientific medical and material aid from the world 
community 
at a news conference at the soviet embassy on friday five 
soviet parliamentary deputies said the official secrecy that 
shrouded the aftermath of the april 26 1986 fire and explosion at 
the chernobyl reactor was a damaging mistake because it masked the 
scope and scale of the disaster 
in addition they said efforts to clean up radiation 
contamination and deal with the medical effects of the accident 
might have been far more advanced by now if most foreign assistance 
had not been rejected 
the radiation that spewed from the plant poisoned millions of 
acres of farmland and forests in the ukraine alone it is now 
believed to pose a potential health threat to at least 4 million 
soviets especially children pregnant women and the elderly 
delegation members said cases of leukemia and thyroid cancer are 
appearing 
and scores of thousands of homes and apartments will have to be 
found and new jobs as well for those evacuated from 
contaminated regions 
i know there were offers of help from foreign organizations 
but they were turned down said kakimbek s salykov the 
delegation leader and chairman of the supreme soviets committee on 
ecology and rational use of natural resources 
we are going to investigate who was the person who ruled that 
such offers be turned down he said 
salykov contrasted the aftermath of chernobyl to the earthquake 
that devastated large sections of soviet armenia on dec 7 1988 
and triggered an outpouring of aid from around the world 
he said he believes the difference in the official attitude was 
caused by the fact that chernobyl occurred at the beginning of 
soviet president mikhail s gorbachevs policy of glasnost or 
openness 
the earthquake occurred when the policies of openness and 
reform were quite well developed he said so all offers were 
accepted 
lev a kuznetsov a member of the delegation said it is now 
clear that in the case of chernobyl the assistance required from 
the world community will be required for a long period of time 
it is very sad for us that it is four years after the 
catastrophe that we parliamentarians have to talk to you like 
that he said 
as to the chernobyl reactor it is considered obsolete and 
accident prone and will be shut down permanently either this 
