<DOCNO> AP900428-0014 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
managers of the savannah river nuclear weapons 
plant in south carolina put some of its workers at an unnecessarily 
high risk of gross contamination by plutonium according to an 
energy department audit report 
plutonium a key ingredient in nuclear warheads is one of the 
most toxic elements known lethal lung doses of plutonium are 
measured in the billionths of a gram 
the defense contractor that runs the plant westinghouse 
electric corp said friday it was taking action to correct the 
problem it was discovered during a twomonth probe of health 
safety and environmental conditions at savannah river which makes 
plutonium and other special materials for nuclear weapons 
the audit ended march 23 and results were made available friday 
at the energy department which owns savannah river and 16 other 
major nuclear arms plants and laboratories 
the audit team of federal officials and private contractors said 
they found a potentially dangerous combination of problems at a 
building called the sed facility which is on the grounds of 
savannah rivers research laboratory near aiken sc 
dean hoffman a westinghouse spokesman said the sed facility 
performs classified work and that he could not comment on it beyond 
saying the problems were being fixed 
the auditors said they were concerned about conditions in an 
area of the facility that contained glove boxes or work stations 
that allowed workers to handle plutonium with leadlined gloves 
inserted through the side of the box 
they said the gloves were severely deteriorated this was 
particularly troubling because the gloves were contaminated with 
plutonium and were in the vicinity of combustible objects 
including plastic plywood cardboard and plexiglass the report 
said 
making matters worse was a lack of adequate fire protection in 
the building the auditors said 
the combination results in a high potential for the spread 
of plutonium contamination to surrounding areas and their 
occupants the report said at another point the report said the 
result could be gross contamination of the sed facility and the 
unspecified number of people working in it 
the nuclear weapons makers learned a painful lesson about the 
dangers of plutonium processing 33 years ago in september 1957 at 
the rocky flats weapons plant in colorado plutonium shavings 
ignited spontaneously in a plexiglass glove box creating a huge 
fire that quickly went out of control and spewed unknown amounts of 
plutonium into the atmosphere just 16 miles from denver 
the problems at the sed facility were rated at category 2 
which the energy department defines as a significant risk but 
not presenting a clear and present danger to workers or the public 
problems of this type are serious enough to require considering 
whether to shut down the facility until corrections are made 
the auditors also said the problems had the potential for 
causing a severe occupational injury illness or fatality or 
destruction of the building 
in all the audit found 11 sets of problems at savannah river in 
the category 2 level besides the sed facility they included 
inadequate procedures for evacuating workers from a highlevel 
nuclear waste storage area in the event of accidental releases of 
radioactivity from nearby processing buildings 
the auditors also gave a category 2 rating to their finding 
that operators and supervisors at savannah rivers waste management 
facilities which are among the largest in the nation have not 
been properly trained to operate the facilities 
hoffman said all 11 of the category 2 concerns are being 
addressed and that most of them already have been corrected 
</TEXT>
