<TEXT>
the environmental protection agency is under 
orders from a federal appeals court to explain why it has not 
written regulations to reduce acid rain 
in a separate but related decision the us circuit court of 
appeals for the district of columbia rejected friday an industry 
challenge to current standards for smoke dust and soot 
the court gave epa 60 days to explain its acid rain position 
the issue could become moot since revisions to clean air 
legislation now before congress are expected to include new 
controls on acid rain precursors such as sulfur dioxide the 
pollutant at issue before the court 
longstanding epa primary regulations aimed at protecting 
public health govern the permissible concentration of sulfur 
dioxide in the groundlevel atmosphere around pollution sources 
such as power plant smokestacks 
the agency also may issue socalled secondary standards 
aimed at protecting economic and other assets without regard to 
health 
sulfur dioxide may be transformed chemically in the atmosphere 
into sulfuric acid which may fall in rain hundreds of miles from 
the pollution source the acid may form a haze in the atmosphere 
that reduces visibility 
the national resources defense council an environmental group 
and several northeastern states argued that the agency must issue a 
secondary sulfur dioxide standard aimed at acid rain one asset to 
be protected was visibility the plaintiffs argued 
epa has taken no formal action indicating that it is moving in 
the direction of making a decision whether or not to establish a 
secondary standard on acid rain wrote judge patricia wald 
while the ruling implies no conclusion as to the merits of 
epas lack of movement the court directed the agency to 
provide us with clear and cogent reasons why it has taken no 
action 
were very pleased that the court agreed with us that the epa 
had not satisfactorily explained why it was continuing to refuse to 
address acid rain said james sevinsky a lawyer in the office of 
new york state attorney general robert abrams 
david doniger a lawyer at the natural resources defense 
council said in one sense this is vindication in another 
sense its a sad commentary on how the legal process works 
in the reagan administration epa argued that more study was 
needed before acid rain could be addressed the bush administration 
favors action and is supporting a farreaching provision in 
congress to require a 10 million ton reduction in annual sulfur 
dioxide emissions almost half the current annual total 
the american iron and steel institute challenged as arbitrary 
and capricious epa air quality standards for particulate matter 
smoke dust and soot on the grounds that they were based on 
inadequate scientific data the court found the federal agencys 
standards conclusions reasonable based on the available data 
the industry group had asked the court to delay its decision 
saying that the national institutes of health is investigating 
allegations that an author of some studies relied on by the epa had 
suppressed evidence of errors 
but those studies were only part of the evidence the epa used 
said the appeals court the significance of the opening of the 
investigation is too speculative to provide grounds for 
delaying its decision said the court 
</TEXT>
