nicaraguan tempers are flaring over 
the new governments devaluation of the national currency which 
has caused prices to shoot up in an economy already plagued by 
soaring inflation 
this new government will be good for nothing everything is 
more expensive a housewife with two children in tow said friday 
to nobody in particular as she walked among the stalls at a managua 
market 
she was one of only a handful of customers at the sprawling 
market which is usually packed with shoppers 
francisca guevara a vendor said she had raised only the price 
of cooking oil because it was imported from guatemala and she 
needed to buy dollars to obtain it 
but ill have to raise the price of everything else too this 
afternoon she said i first have to figure out my costs 
other vendors already had raised their prices 
the 2dayold usbacked government of president violeta 
barrios de chamorro slashed the value of the cordoba in half 
prices for many items increased while the wages of most 
nicaraguans stayed the same many earned just 30 a month before 
the devaluation 
at the new prices a pound of rice one of beans and one of beef 
would cost a total of 205000 cordobas or 146 
mrs chamorro inherited an economy damaged by more than a decade 
of mismanagement by her leftist sandinista precedessors war with 
the usbacked contra rebels and a us trade embargo that has now 
been lifted 
inflation was a worldrecord 36000 percent in 1988 the 
sandinistas managed to bring it down to 1800 percent in 1989 with 
their own austerity program 
the exchange rate of the cordoba went from 70800 to 140000 per 
us dollar in the socalled parallel market thus anyone buying 
dollars at the legal exchange houses that constitute nicaraguas 
parallel market had to pay twice as much friday as thursday 
the official exchange rate had been 53800 cordobas to the 
dollar since the last devaluation april 17 the official market 
sells a limited amount of dollars set aside for importing only 
crucial goods such as medicines oil and fertilizer 
the parallel market provides a greater but still limited amount 
of dollars for less crucial imports but at a higher price 
the black market meets the rest of nicaraguas demand for 
dollars 
the devaluation was a blow to nicaraguans who buy dollars to 
import goods but that was the idea to make it more expensive to 
import goods and cheaper to export nicaraguan items 
the government hopes the move will help cut the countrys trade 
deficit which was 413 million in 1989 
