the moratorium the nations first prohibition of a product of 
genetic engineering forbids commercial use of bovine somatotropin 
bst until june 1 1991 allowing it only for research 
republican gov tommy g thompson who signed the legislation 
friday vetoed an alternative bill that would have forbidden use of 
the protein until six months after its commercial use is approved 
by the us food and drug administration 
thompson said he did not want the moratorium to extend later 
than 1991 because bst use by farmers in other states could put 
wisconsins dairy industry at a market disadvantage 
the minnesota legislature approved a bill thursday establishing 
a oneyear moratorium if the wisconsin legislation became law 
supporters of the hormone warned that wisconsin dairy farmers 
could be hurt if the state became an island surrounded by 
states that permitted its use opponents contended increased 
production could push milk prices down thus driving smaller dairy 
farmers out of business 
democratic sen russell d feingold a leader of the 
legislatures campaign against bst or bovine growth hormone bgh 
called the bill the first moratorium ever on bgh in the nation 
its more than a victory its a start of what will be a 
national movement feingold said 
democratic rep barbara gronemus said that although the new law 
temporarily prevents farmers from buying the drug the republican 
governors vetoes may not prevent marketing of milk from test 
animals 
it appears that the milk from these test herds could be 
used she said im really disappointed about that aspect of 
it to allow the byproducts to go into the food chain is really 
unacceptable to me 
the moratorium stems from concern by the legislature that 
consumers will be leery of milk from treated cows reducing sales 
of cheese and other dairy products important to wisconsins economy 
some farm organizations argued the drugs ability to increase 
milk production as much as 20 percent would help corporate farms 
with large herds to dominate the market putting smaller family 
farms out of business 
its not feasible for ourselves to build a wall around this 
state and prevent new technology from coming in here the 
governor said its going to be a sad day in wisconsin when we 
stop research 
the diet given treated cattle contains more fat than usual 
critics say the process means added production expense that only 
big farms can afford 
jeffrey remsik a spokesman for the animal health institute 
said chemical companies that are developing bst are disappointed 
with the moratorium 
the new law damages the dairy states chances of attracting 
biotechnology research remsik said the governors action tends 
to undermine the traditional federal regulatory system and sends a 
strong message that wisconsin is not interested in new 
technologies he said 
remsik said a court may have to decide whether the measure 
thompson signed actually triggers the minnesota moratorium 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

