european community leaders today opened 
talks to consider french and german appeals for faster movement 
toward a political merger of their 12 nations 
french president francois mitterrand prime minister margaret 
thatcher of britain and west german chancellor helmut kohl joined a 
stream of prime ministers and their aides at the medieval dublin 
castle on an overcast day in dublin the irish capital 
the western european nations who already plan to form a single 
open market by the end of 1992 are now beginning to discuss ways 
of bringing their political systems into closer alignment 
reacting to the profound political changes in eastern europe 
mitterrand and kohl are urging faster movement toward a political 
union 
mrs thatcher was expected to oppose their calls for a political 
union of the economic community trading bloc by 1993 
ec officials were also expected to discuss plans for 
reunification of the two germanys the original reason for todays 
meeting before the french and german appeals for political unity 
surfaced 
also on the agenda is a plan to forge closer relations with the 
emerging democracies in eastern europe and draw them closer to the 
west 
before discussing political union the leaders endorsed a 
threestage plan for bringing east germany into the european 
community the agreement would benefit east germanys backward 
economy by bringing it into a trade bloc of 320 million people 
west germany is already an influential ec member 
the first stage calls for an interim adjustment period starting 
july 2 when the two germanys merge their currencies the second 
stage begins with formal unification of the two germanys which is 
planed for late next year from then on community laws will apply 
to what is now east german territory but it will be allowed 
certain exemptions for example on rules about state subsidies and 
environmental regulations in the final stage for which no 
deadline has been set all european community rules would apply 
security was tight in the citys center for the gathering 
authorities banned aircraft from flying over the 13thcentury 
castle and deployed the rangers an elite antiterrorist unit 
