saying british justice stinks an 
irishwoman flew home to freedom saturday her conviction for 
terrorist conspiracy quashed in a sensational british court ruling 
martina shanahan who arrived in dublin on her 25th birthday 
was released with fellow prisoners john mccann and finbar cullen 
who flew to ireland separately each had served 2 years of a 
25year sentence 
a british appeals court ruled friday that the 1988 trial of the 
socalled winchester three could have been prejudiced by a 
british cabinet ministers remarks 
the three were jailed for allegedly conspiring to murder tom 
king then the governments secretary of state for northern ireland 
during their trial in the western england city of winchester 
the government changed the law to allow juries to draw negative 
inferences from a suspects silence under police questioning 
king now defense secretary was prominent in defending the 
change he said on television that defendants should not have the 
right to remain silent 
the appeal court agreed kings remarks could have prejudiced the 
trial and ordered the three freed the government immediately 
ordered them deported 
the case of the winchester three was the latest in a series of 
embarrassments for britain over the justice it metes out to irish 
suspects 
in october the guildford four were released having served 
14 years of a life sentence for bombings that killed five people 
an appeals judge ruled that police lied about some of the evidence 
then there are the birmingham six jailed for life in 1975 
for bombings that killed 19 people their supporters insist they 
are victims of a miscarriage of justice and the government has 
agreed to have certain aspects of the case reviewed 
for the irish the case of the winchester three struck 
particularly close to home 
unlike the guildford and birmingham convicts most of whom come 
from northern ireland where the irish republican army wages its war 
against britain the winchester three come from the irish republic 
none seemed to fit the stereotype of the hardened fighter for 
the ira which wants to unite protestantdominated northern ireland 
with the overwhelmingly roman catholic republic of ireland 
