<TEXT>
lithuanias president and a soviet government 
spokesman on saturday praised a frenchwest german proposal to 
defuse tensions raising the possibility it could lead to a 
compromise between moscow and vilnius 
the kremlin has shut down shipments of oil restricted natural 
gas and cut supplies of manufactured goods and food supplies to 
lithuania on saturday a soviet government official said coal 
supplies had been cut as well 
a letter from french president francois mitterrand and west 
german chancellor helmut kohl proposed lithuania suspend some laws 
backing up its march 11 declaration of independence but did not 
suggest repealing the declaration itself 
we consider that this is not far from the line that the soviet 
leadership has been pursuing from the very beginning arkady 
maslennikov a spokesman for soviet president mikhail s gorbachev 
told a kremlin briefing we consider this a constructive signal 
lithuanian leaders also are showing the understanding that 
there must be a return to the road of reason maslennikov said 
in the lithuanian capital of vilnius president vytautas 
landsbergis told a news conference he considered the proposal a 
positive step said lithuanian journalist eduardas potashinskas 
some may interpret this letter as a concession to the 
categorical position of the soviet union he quoted landsbergis 
as saying we see it differently 
we will suggest that the initiative of these leaders not end 
with this letter he said 
on friday lithuanian premier kazimiera prunskiene said the 
frenchwest german proposal was the limit to compromise that 
lithuania could accept the lithuanian leadership said it will 
bring the proposal before the baltic republics legislature this 
week for debate 
in order to begin talks on the basis of the kohlmitterrand 
letter the two sides must find a formula that takes into account 
their opposing views of the independence declaration 
lithuania has sent several delegations to moscow in hopes of 
arranging toplevel meetings but there have been few such contacts 
gorbachev says lithuania must renounce the declaration 
landsbergis and the lithuanian leadership say they cannot back down 
on the declaration but the laws implementing it and the schedule 
are negotiable 
the republic says the declaration only recognizes the legal 
status lithuania held before its forcible annexation along with 
that of neighboring latvia and estonia by the soviet union in 
1940 
western countries including the united states never recognized 
the incorporation of the baltic states but also have not recognized 
lithuanias declaration 
the issue is a test for gorbachev who faces several nationalist 
and ethnic crises the parliament of estonia has voted to become 
independent at an unspecified later date and latvia is scheduled 
to vote on the issue this week 
gorbachev and soviet premier nikolai i ryzhkov have demanded 
that lithuania reverse its opposition to its youths being drafted 
into the soviet army return communist party buildings being used 
by lithuanias independent communists and repeal a law on 
citizenship they regarded as discriminatory 
the soviet military has seized some buildings in vilnius and 
conducted a series of military maneuvers an effort to pressure the 
republic of 38 million people 
officials say about 10000 lithuanians already are out of work 
because of the economic blockade from moscow and the soviet news 
agency tass said experts believe the figure will grow to 35000 by 
tuesday 
the republics only oil refinery shut down last week and it is 
receiving only a small share of its normal allotment of natural gas 
supplies of gasoline to private car owners has been restricted 
to about 7 gallons a month and long lines have formed at gas 
stations many people are walking 
official vilnius radio reported late friday that publication of 
newspapers in the republic would be severely restricted this week 
but it said lithuania had enough newsprint to continue publishing 
the papers 
soviet authorities have restricted western reporters from 
traveling to lithuania except by invitation on trips organized by 
the foreign ministry the associated press was not invited on one 
trip currently under way 
vladimir kosyunin deputy chairman of the soviet state supply 
committee told tass that coal supplies had been curtailed as well 
much of that coal comes from poland and lithuania already owes 
about 1 million rubles for coal supplies he said 
kosyunin told tass it would take only a matter of days to 
restore normal shipments to lithuania if a political settlement is 
reached the situation is not yet irreversible but it will be 
much more difficult to resolve the problem later 
</TEXT>
