early saturday the 15 billion telescope was sent health and 
safety instructions to operate on its own a day earlier the 
electronic instruments had automatically shut down when they sensed 
trouble with one of two highgain antennas and when opening the 
lens cover made the telescope move 
the highgain antennas send data back to earth at high speed 
we are continuing to remain in good communication with the 
telescope said dave drachlis of the goddard space flight center 
in greenbelt md he said systems other than the antenna were 
running properly 
ground controllers at goddard tried moving the good highgain 
antenna but noticed the other antenna also was turning 
they basically stopped the process and scratched their 
heads for a bit drachlis said 
jean olivier a deputy project manager for hubble said various 
options are being considered to aim the good antenna without moving 
the bad one if computer programs must be adapted to get data from 
just one antenna it will be somewhat of a hit 
neither olivier nor mike harrington director of orbital 
verification ventured to say how much that might affect scientific 
returns 
the problems with the antennas have delayed calibration tests 
that ground controllers must conduct on the telescopes five 
scientific instruments 
drachlis said delaying those tests was not a major problem 
the overnight commands put the instruments on hold the state in 
which they will spend much of their time awaiting signals to wake 
up and study the heavens 
engineers can send commands to the telescope via its secondary 
lowgain antennas but that system which is considerably slower 
isnt useful for scientific data 
in a news conference from discovery astronaut bruce mccandless 
said hes not surprised a very complex system like this may have 
