<TEXT>
about 200 aliens in detention centers may be 
paroled in an experiment that could signal a change in the way the 
united states views aliens seeking political asylum according to 
report published sunday 
under current rules aliens requesting asylum are held in 
custody while their cases are reviewed a process that can take 
from a few days to years 
the new program starting in several cities this week would let 
selected detainees remain free while the immigration and 
naturalization service reviews their cases the new york times 
reported 
participants in the program would have to post a bond of between 
500 to 2500 establish their identities and have jobs 
residences and lawyers or other accredited representatives 
alien also would have to agree to report monthly to the ins and 
return to detention or leave the country if ordered the newspaper 
reported 
the 18month experimental program will be in new york miami 
los angeles and san francisco 
the ins said there are 5000 to 6000 aliens in its detention 
centers not including cubans from the mariel boatlift who are 
considered criminals 
the director of the refugee project for the lawyers committee 
for human rights arthur c helton said the program stems from 
talks he had with the new ins commissioner gene mcnary 
we hope that this release project will demonstrate that many 
refugees are being unnecessarily incarcerated in the united 
states helton told the times 
this project may indeed signal the beginning of the end of one 
the harshest elements of the inss detention policy 
