<TEXT>
in the mathematics of wall street a 9 percent 
interest rate equals a distinct minus for the stock market 
at least thats the way the numbers crunched in the past week as 
yields on longterm treasury bonds surpassed the 9 percent level 
for the first time in nearly a year 
there was a time a decade or so ago when stock and bond 
traders might have exulted to see interest rates at anywhere near 9 
percent in those inflationwracked days yields all along the 
creditmarket spectrum held persistently in two digits 
but now things are different or at least they were supposed to 
be as the 1990s dawned amid hopes for slow but steady growth in 
business activity and corporate profits without much interference 
from inflationary pressures 
at the start of the year longterm government bonds yielded 
slightly less than 8 percent and many forecasters voiced 
confidence that they were headed lower still 
lower rates figured to stimulate spending by both businesses and 
consumers and to benefit the stock market by reducing the 
comparative allure of interestbearing investments 
such visions quickly began to fade however when rates jumped 
in japan west germany and other important us trading partners 
dragging domestic rates higher as well 
optimism in the bond market has been dealt a second blow of late 
by data for the first quarter of the year showing inflation rates 
at their highest levels since the early 1980s 
now talk is spreading in the financial world that the federal 
reserve once again finds itself facing a choice between two 
notveryhappy alternatives 
the classic dilemma of higher inflation amidst pockets of 
economic weakness is confronting the fed said anthony vignola 
an analyst at kidder peabody amp co 
if the fed tightens policy and raises rates it will incur the 
displeasure of the administration and risk upsetting a delicate 
but deteriorating international framework 
more important the fed risks stifling economic growth which 
has suffered from continued weakness in manufacturing and housing 
as longterm rates rose to 9 percent the stock market averages 
headed down the dow jones average of 30 industrials dropped 5090 
this past week to 264505 on top of a 5585point loss the week 
before 
the new york stock exchange composite index fell 192 to 18074 
the american stock exchange market value index lost 532 to 34264 
and the nasdaq composite index for the overthecounter market was 
down 781 at 41798 
volume on the big board averaged 13559 million shares a day 
against 14902 million the week before 
whatever other negative possibilities it presents the 
combination of slow growth and high interest rates makes for gloom 
among stockmarket investors as they contemplate the outlook for 
corporate earnings 
unfortunately the economys slowmotion performance probably 
wont do much to bring inflation down any time soon says the 
current edition of the merrill lynch market letter 
thats because increases in labor costs show no signs of 
slowing and recent gains in productivity have been meager 
corporate profits are likely to remain under pressure for the 
foreseeable future as the economy plods along and inflation stays 
high 
a good many optimists still hold out hope that todays high 
rates by acting as a drag on business activity might improve the 
chance for lower borrowing costs at some point later in the year 
talk of at least a return to 8 percent government bond yields by 
the fall is still prevalent on wall street 
but upbeat interestrate forecasts tend to meet with a lot of 
skepticism these days if only because of the way the batch 
produced last winter turned out 
