as one economist edward yardeni puts it lowquality 
borrowers who need to finance very risky activities are being 
turned away by the bankers but that leaves more lendable funds for 
highquality borrowers 
by another less conventional definition consumers businesses 
and governmental units at all levels are snared in a credit trap 
many of them destined for a long painful experience and perhaps 
bankruptcy 
by the conventional definitions the economy should avoid 
recession in 1990 and conceivably grow faster than in 1989 by the 
other it is already in the midst of a dangerous destructive 
creditrestraint recession 
the more optimistic scenario comes from a revue of national 
statistics including gross national product incomes shortterm 
loan data money in circulation and other figures used by 
government economists 
the negative conclusion comes from discussions with heads of 
households with folks who must meet the weektoweek bills if 
they cant it is assumed that the impact will spread with sales 
profits tax receipts falling 
the most common conventional definition of recession is two 
successive quarters of shrinking gross national product it hasnt 
occurred officially since the last recession ended in 1982 the 
longest gap of the century 
albert sindlingers definition is the unconventional one 
arrived at by talking directly to heads of households and asking 
them how their personal finances are holding up they arent he 
says families are in trouble 
how does he know from wallingford penn his staff telephones 
heads of households in the 48 contiguous states 1000 different 
ones each week a practice now approaching 13000 consecutive days 
the heads of households are asked these questions 
is your total combined household annual income up or the same 
as it was six months ago 
will the total combined household annual income for the next 
six months remain the same or be higher than now 
in the next six months will there be more or the same number 
of jobs where you work 
in the next six months do you anticipate better or the same 
business conditions in your community 
if the respondent answers any of the four questions with a 
negative response that household is said to have negative 
household liquidity roughly stated as inability or unwillingness 
to maintain current standards 
sindlinger tells his business clients that a state is declared 
to be in recession if household liquidity falls below 50 percent 
two states were in recession in january 1989 29 by december 34 in 
january and 41 in march 
the only states solidly beyond recession in march were illinois 
ohio and michigan four others washington wisconsin minnesota 
and indiana registered less than 55 percent meaning they have 
avoided recession by a lesser margin 
new england says sindlinger is in the deepest recession with 
a reading of only 384 percent five rocky mountain states and 12 
southeastern states are also listed in poor shape 
the rest except for the midwest states and washington are in 
shallower recessions sindlinger says 
using more conventional yardsticks yardeni sees no sign of a 
credit crunch in the shortterm loan data clearly he says 
shortterm credit continues to expand 
if there is a credit crunch out there we should see it he 
says it would show up in the statistics so far we dont see 
it 
but using information from another source sindlinger finds the 
credit crunch already is here that households are severely 
pinched and that as far as hes concerned most of the nation is 
in a recession 
</TEXT>
