<DOCNO> AP900428-0158 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a trade association of futures fund managers has stepped into 
the turf battle for jurisdiction over stockindex futures with a 
simple plea if there has to be a change in regulators at least 
dont change the rules 
the request made to members of congress by the managed futures 
trade association may be a further indication that the futures 
industry is moving grudgingly toward acceptance of a change in the 
federal agency with authority over index futures 
the securities and exchange commission which regulates stock 
trading has long sought jurisdiction over index futures financial 
instruments that are derived from stock prices but regulated like 
all futures contracts by the commodity futures trading commission 
critics say the cftc is too lax and too cozy with the futures 
industry to properly safeguard the public interest 
the managed futures trading association is a pittsburghbased 
group representing 150 professional futures traders who manage an 
estimated 8 billion in public investment funds said jane martin 
executive director 
in a letter sent earlier this month to key members of congress 
the groups chairman kenneth tropin said the associations first 
choice would be to leave index futures under the jurisdiction of 
the cftc because it has expertise that the sec lacks in the area of 
futures trading 
but should congress decide to transfer authority over index 
futures to the sec tropin said the sec should not be allowed to 
change existing regulations that have been developed by the cftc 
stockindex futures contracts should continue to be regulated 
as futures contracts and not as equity instruments regardless of 
which regulatory agency is granted the responsibility to enforce 
such laws tropin said in his letter 
maintaining futurestrading rules as they currently exist he 
said will provide for a smooth regulatory transition and avoid 
the application of potentially duplicative disruptive and 
inconsistent regulations 
the next congressional hearing on the issue is a scheduled may 8 
session before the senate agriculture committee according to cftc 
spokesman david gary 
the jurisdictional issue has heated up since the 1987 stock 
market crash which some experts believe was exacerbated by 
computerdriven program trading strategies involving rapid 
simultaneous trades of huge amounts of both stocks and stockindex 
futures 
futures industry leaders contend index futures markets actually 
prevented an even steeper drop in stock prices on oct 19 1987 
when the dow jones industrial average fell 508 points 
sec chairman richard breeden and treasury secretary nicholas 
brady are urging congress to give the sec jurisdiction over 
stockindex futures which are contracts to buy and sell baskets of 
stocks such as those represented by the standard amp poors 500 index 
chicagos worldleading futures exchanges the chicago board of 
trade and the chicago mercantile exchange oppose the proposed 
regulatory change but earlier this month top officials of the 
chicago exchanges indicated that if any change in jurisdiction 
occurs they would prefer a proposal by rep dan glickman dkan 
and rep dennis eckart dohio for a superregulator that would 
have authority over all stock and futures trading 
</TEXT>
