<TEXT>
the history unfolding in eastern europe could 
have farreaching consequences for years to come and speculation 
about the impact has preoccupied investors in the worlds financial 
centers 
currencies have been bought and sold based on theories about 
what will happen to various economies particularly west germanys 
stocks have gained and lost as traders assess which companies will 
benefit from business opportunities 
the melding of the two germanies however might not mean all 
that much outside their joined borders a new study suggests 
the impact of german economic unification on other countries 
is relatively modest as the additional investment demand is not 
large relative to global investment and a disproportionate share of 
that investment demand is met by domestic german savings says 
the study by two members of the federal reserve boards staff in 
washington 
west german chancellor helmut kohl and prime minister lothar de 
maiziere of east germany confirmed at a meeting last week that the 
two nations soon will share an economy 
although many details must still be worked out there likely 
will be one german economy by july 2 west germanys agreement to 
swap most east german marks for its own marks at a 1to1 rate 
cleared the way for the process to begin a new currency is 
expected to go into circulation next autumn 
the fed analysts say the link ultimately will lead to an 
acceleration of investment and growth in a united germany a real 
appreciation of the deutschmark and a reduction in germanys 
current account surplus 
the boost in consumer demand expected to occur as the german 
economies blend is one of the outgrowths of unification that will 
directly affect the rest of the world 
after plugging various assumptions into a statistical model the 
study projects that the us trade deficit will contract but 
joseph e gagnon one of the authors said the shrinkage will be 
small considering the magnitude of us world trade 
the annual improvement in the us current account balance will 
peak at 15 billion a year after three years the current account 
is the countrys broadest measure of foreign trade and includes the 
exchange of goods and services as well as certain financial 
transactions it ran a deficit of 1059 billion in 1989 
the marks increased value in terms of other major currencies 
particularly the dollar also will affect germanys trading 
partners a stronger mark will lower the bill for the foreign goods 
that will be imported into germany to satisfy the bigger consumer 
appetite 
the dismantling of barriers to trade and investment and the 
enhanced efficiency of the east german economy will spur an 
economic boom as the integration proceeds domestic west german 
savings though are expected to be sufficient to support most of 
this investment surge 
changes elsewhere in eastern europe might have greater potential 
to influence economic variables in the united states 
the study says the ongoing liberalization of eastern europe 
can be expected to have additional consequences for the united 
states and other countries 
but it added while the potential demands for investment are 
much larger in the other eastern european countries as a group the 
reduction in barriers and improvement in efficiency will proceed 
more slowly in those countries than the pace assumed for east 
germany in this paper thus the immediate and mediumterm impact 
of liberalization in eastern europe remains uncertain 
the study the global economic implications of german 
unification is part of the feds international finance 
discussion series it represents the opinions of the authors only 
and is not an official fed view 
</TEXT>
